The battle of St. Alban’s, though in itself a mere skirmish, developed the inextinguishable feuds of the civil war. The quarrels os Lords Devon and Bonvile‚ the feud which came from the marriage ol Thomas Nevil, son ol the Earl ol Salisbury, with the niece ot Lord Cromwell, between the bridegroom and Thos. Percy, Lord Egremont; the anger of the House ol York at being excluded from the King's councils, and the sight os Somerset and the Queen in the conduct os all affairs, stirred bad blood enough. The Queen, aster the loss os three among her more zealous partisans, made up her mind to the ruin ol =Y0rk, and the ad- vantage which York gained at St. Alban’s made him equally determined to secure himself from risk by obtaining a recognised position in the state, under the authority os Parliament. The King did his best to mediate between the parties, and effected srom time to time formal but hollow reconciliations. But nothing could erase the bloodshed os St. Alban’s, and as Gascoigne is lond of saying ‘sanguis sanguinem tetigit)

The Parliament ol 1455 met on July 11, and the Commons presented Sir John Wenlok as their Speaker. They were soon prorogued to Nov. 12, for the harvest was at hand. On Nov. 19 York was again appointed Protector, for the King’s mind was again affected, though not, it appears, so seriously on this occasion.
